Supervised vs.Unsupervised Learning

In contrast with the unsupervised methods covered in previous labs, analyses involving a pre-determined outcome variable are described as supervised learning tasks. For these tasks, well adopt the following modeling framework: \[Y = f(\mathbf{X}) + \epsilon\]

  • \(Y\) is the outcome variable
  • \(f()\) is an unknown function of \(\mathbf{X}\) (a matrix of input variables)
  • \(\epsilon\) is a random error term that is independent of the variables in \(\mathbf{X}\) and has a mean of zero

Thus, the outcome variable is modeled by a systematic component, which uses information from \(\mathbf{X}\) (sometimes referred to as signal), and error, which is sometimes referred to as noise.

\(~\)

Motivating Example

The data frame rmr (given below) contains the body weights (lbs) and resting metabolic rates (kcal/day), abbreviated RMR, for a random sample of \(n = 44\) US adult women.

rmr <- read.csv("https://remiller1450.github.io/data/RMR.csv")
head(rmr)
##   weight_lbs rate_kcal
## 1     104.79      1079
## 2     106.68      1146
## 3     108.78      1115
## 4     110.46      1161
## 5     120.96      1325
## 6     128.94      1351

Expressing this scenario using the framework of the previous section, we might be interested in:

\[\text{RMR} = f(\text{Weight}) + \epsilon\]

  • In words, a womans RMR is some function of their body weight and noise/variability
  • One goal of supervised learning is to estimate \(f()\) using our data to help us understand this relationship

Data visualization is a useful tool for helping us decide how to approach this task:

ggplot(rmr, aes(x = weight_lbs, y = rate_kcal)) + geom_point() + geom_rug() + theme_minimal()

From the scatter plot, it seems plausible to assume a linear relationship between body weight and RMR. In other words, a straight line might provide a good model for these data, but which line should we use?

Measuring Performance

To evaluate a model we must define an objective measure of performance. For numeric outcomes, the most common performance metric is mean squared error (MSE), and the corresponding quantity root-mean squared error (RMSE):

\[MSE = \tfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2 \text{ and }RMSE = \sqrt{\text{MSE}}\]

  • In this notation, \(\hat{y}_i\) is the models prediction for the data-point indexed by \(i\)
    • For example, if \(x_i = 150\) (ie: a bodyweight of 150 lbs) the blue model (or \(\hat{f}_{\text{blue}}(X)\)) predicts an RMR of 1200, or \(\hat{y}_i = 1200\)
  • The MSE of a model describes the average squared error of the models predictions
  • RMSE attempts to undo the squaring, which provides an error measurement with same units as the outcome variable

For the 44 women in these data, Model #1 has an RMSE of 154.27, Model #2 has an RMSE of 167.07, and Model #3 an RMSE of 179.15. What do these numbers mean (in practical terms)? Which model should we prefer?

Note: When MSE or RMSE is calculated for the same data that was used to train the model (ie: estimate \(f()\)) we call the resulting quantity the models in-sample MSE/RMSE. If the calculation uses predictions for data that was not used to train the model well use the phrase out-of-sample MSE/RMSE.

Linear Regression

We can summarize the modeling approach from this labs introduction (ie: determining how to estimate \(f()\) using the sample data) using two steps:

  1. We determined the type of structural relationship that wanted our model to utilize (ie: a straight line)
  2. We found an instance of that type that led to the best performance (ie: the straight line with the lowest RMSE)

These steps lead us to the method of linear regression, a class of structured models that are:

  1. parametric - meaning they specify the functional form of \(f()\) (ie: a straight line, a quadratic polynomial, etc.)
  2. statistical - meaing they specify a probability distribution for \(\epsilon\), the error term

The first step in a regression analysis is to describe the models functional form. Statisticians will call this a population-level model, and it is typically expressed using symbols:

\[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1X + \epsilon\]

  • \(Y\) is the outcome variable
  • \(X\) is the independent or explanatory variable
  • The intercept and slope, \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\), are parameters of the model (making it a parametric model)
  • \(\epsilon\) is a random error (making it a statistical model)

The key pieces of this model are the intercept and slope, which in theory could be anything. However, wed like them to be such that the RMSE of the model is minimized. This can be done using a method known as ordinary least squares:

So, the slope and intercept are found such that they minimize the squared error. Additional mathematical details can be found here. Once the optimal slope and intercept have been estimated from the sample data, we can provide an estimated model using numbers (rather than symbols). We refer to any quantity involving estimates based upon sample data using a \(\hat{ }\) or hat. For example, we may have the estimated model:

\[\hat{Y} = 810 + 3.4X\]

To summarize:

  1. Methods like data visualization are used to decide upon the type of relationship between predictors and an outcome variable.
  2. We specify a model whose function form captures that relationship, for example: \(\text{Metabolism} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Weight} + \epsilon\)
  3. We estimate the models unknown parameters using the sample data, for example \(\hat{\beta}_0 = 810\) kcal and \(\hat{\beta}_1 = 3.4\) kcal/lb

Steps 1 and 2 are things that we must decide upon ourselves, but once we do so R can handle Step 3 (demonstrated below):

## Sample data
rmr <- read.csv("https://remiller1450.github.io/data/RMR.csv")

## Model specification
my_form <- formula(rate_kcal ~ weight_lbs)

## Estimation of the model
lm_fit <- lm(my_form, data = rmr)
coefficients(lm_fit)
## (Intercept)  weight_lbs 
##   811.22667     3.36168

In R, we generally will use a formula object to define our models functional form. In this example, we use that formula as input to the lm() function, which estimates the parameters linear model via ordinary least squares using the given model formula and the sample data. In this example, we used the coefficients() function to extract the estimated slope and intercept from the fitted model.

We could use these coefficients construct a visualization of our model:

ggplot(rmr, aes(x = weight_lbs, y = rate_kcal)) + geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept = coefficients(lm_fit)[1], 
              slope = coefficients(lm_fit)[2])

Finally, you should note that we arent limited to using a single predictor. Linear regression generalizes to the form:

\[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1X_1 + \beta_2X_2 + \ldots \beta_pX_p + \epsilon\]

In each dimension of \(\mathbf{X}\) there is a slope. We visualized this in 3-dimensions our the plotly lab.

Feature Expansion

Linear regression imposes a rigid functional form on \(f()\) that cannot adequately capture non-linear relationships. However, we can use a strategy known as feature expansion to overcome this limitation. For example, lets expand the weight variable in the RMR data by creating new columns representing weight, weight squared, and weight cubed using the poly() function:

rmr2 = data.frame(poly(rmr$weight_lbs, degree = 3, raw = TRUE), rmr$rate_kcal)
colnames(rmr2) = c("X1","X2","X3","rate_kcal")
head(rmr2)
##       X1       X2      X3 rate_kcal
## 1 104.79 10980.94 1150693      1079
## 2 106.68 11380.62 1214085      1146
## 3 108.78 11833.09 1287203      1115
## 4 110.46 12201.41 1347768      1161
## 5 120.96 14631.32 1769805      1325
## 6 128.94 16625.52 2143695      1351

We can then fit a linear regression model using these three predictors:

poly3_mod <- lm(rate_kcal ~ X1 + X2 + X3, data = rmr2)
coefficients(poly3_mod)
##   (Intercept)            X1            X2            X3 
##  4.005720e+02  9.541122e+00 -2.756257e-02  3.664196e-05

Importantly, we could perform the polynomial expansion inside of the lm() function using the original rmr data frame as the models input data:

poly3_mod_alt <- lm(rate_kcal ~ poly(weight_lbs, degree = 3, raw = TRUE), data = rmr)
coefficients(poly3_mod_alt)
##                               (Intercept) 
##                              4.005720e+02 
## poly(weight_lbs, degree = 3, raw = TRUE)1 
##                              9.541122e+00 
## poly(weight_lbs, degree = 3, raw = TRUE)2 
##                             -2.756257e-02 
## poly(weight_lbs, degree = 3, raw = TRUE)3 
##                              3.664196e-05

The names lm() gives to these coefficients are a little messy, but putting poly() directly in the model formula makes visualization much easier.

Visualizing this model will require a new strategy since we cannot simply draw a line using a slope and intercept. Thus, our approach will consist of these steps:

  1. Generating a dense sequence of hypothetical body weights (or the models predictor(s) in general terms)
  2. Using the model to predict RMR (the models outcome) for every body weight in this sequence
  3. Connecting these predictions using line segments, which will closely approximate the model if the sequence was sufficiently dense
## Create a sequence of 200 values from the min to max bodyweight
xx = with(rmr, seq(min(weight_lbs), max(weight_lbs), length.out = 200))

## Predictions over the sequence
yy = predict(poly3_mod_alt, data.frame(weight_lbs = xx))

## Plot the predictions using geom_line()
ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = rmr$weight_lbs, y = rmr$rate_kcal)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = xx, y = yy), col = "red", size = 2)

Here we see that the polynomial expansion makes our model more flexible, thereby allowing its predictions to get closer to the observed y-values.

Two additional feature expansion strategies, splines and discretization, are demonstrated below:

## Discretize into 3 categories using cut()
des_mod = lm(rate_kcal ~ cut(weight_lbs, breaks = 3), data = rmr)

## Spline expansion using bs()
library(splines)
spline_mod = lm(rate_kcal ~ bs(weight_lbs, degree = 2, knots = c(150,200,250)), data = rmr)

## New seq predictions for each
yd = predict(des_mod, data.frame(weight_lbs = xx))
ys = predict(spline_mod, data.frame(weight_lbs = xx))

## Visualizations of each
ggplot()+ 
  geom_point(aes(x = rmr$weight_lbs, y = rmr$rate_kcal)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = xx, y = ys), col = "green", size = 2) +
  geom_line(aes(x = xx, y = yd), col = "purple", size = 2)

Without getting too far into the details, discretization (using cut()) separates a numeric predictor into categories that are either equally spaced (if an integer is given for the breaks argument) or split at certain cut-points (if a vector is given for the breaks argument). Splines, implemented using bs() and other similar functions, will fit piece-wise polynomials of a specified degree that are joined together at locations called knots. Additional information can be found here.

K-nearest Neighbors

Even with strategies like feature expansion, regression can still be limited in its ability to detect highly localized patterns. In these circumstances, we might consider modeling algorithms that do not assume a parametric functional form when estimating \(f()\), with \(k\)-nearest neighbors (KNN) being a simple example.

KNN Algorithm:

Standardizing \(\mathbf{X}\) is an important preliminary step in \(k\)-nearest neighbors. Because neighbors are found using distance, all variables should be on the same scale.

Next, consider a grid of target values, or points in the \(p\)-dimensional space corresponding to \(\mathbf{X}\) that wed like the model to predict.

  1. For each target value, calculate its distance from each observation in \(\mathbf{X}\)
  2. Sort these distances from smallest to largest
  3. Select \(k\) data-points in order of smallest distance
  4. Aggregate the observed \(y\) values of the selected data-points to obtain a predicted \(Y\) value (either a simple average, or inverse distance weighted average)

Visualizing KNN

KKN models can be fit using the knn.reg() function in the FNN library.

You should note that theres also a knn() function that well use in the future for classification tasks (predicting categorical outcomes).

library(FNN)
knn_fit = knn.reg(train = rmr$weight_lbs, ## Observed Predictors
                  test = data.frame(xx),  ## Targets to Predict
                  y = rmr$rate_kcal,      ## Observed Outcome
                  k = 5)                  ## Neighbors

Models from knn.reg are not compatible with the predict() function, so we need to slightly adjust our visualization approach. Instead, the target values for which predictions are desired are supplied using the test argument.

We can then use the results stored in the pred component of the fitted model to visualize the KNN models estimate of \(f()\):

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = rmr$weight_lbs, y = rmr$rate_kcal)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = xx, y = knn_fit$pred), col = "blue", size = 2)

\(~\)

Choosing \(k\)

Similar to \(k\)-means clustering, the data analyst using KNN must specify a value of \(k\) at the start of the algorithm, and the optimal value of \(k\) will vary across different applications.

  • A larger value of \(k\) (using more neighbors) increases stability (ie: less potential for overfitting) but also increases bias (ie: reduced ability to detect local patterns in the data)
  • A smaller value of \(k\) (using fewer neighbors) will decrease bias but also decrease stability

This tension is commonly referred to as the bias-variance trade-off, and it applies to all modeling approaches.

In our next lab, well learn how to navigate the bias-variance trade-off using cross-validation as a guiding framework. For now, you should choose a reasonable value of \(k\) using visual inspection.
